thread.title: Massive fall and early winter trout plants announced to boost fishing opportunities in west side lakes
thread.title_full: Massive fall and early winter trout plants announced to boost fishing opportunities in west side lakes | The Seattle Times

author: Mark Yuasa
title: Massive fall and early winter trout plants announced to boost fishing opportunities in west side lakes
text:
The fall and early-winter trout fisheries in west-side lakes are getting a big boost for angling opportunities.
“Another piece of our lowland lake trout program is getting underway this week as we plant thousands of trout and steelhead in local lakes,” said Larry Phillips, the state Fish and Wildlife inland fish manager. “We hear from many people who appreciate this opportunity.”
The entire plant will total 125,850 rainbow trout or steelhead going into 48 west side lakes in Grays Harbor, King, Snohomish, Thurston, Whatcom, Skagit,, Lewis, Cowlitz, Clark, Klickitat, Jefferson, Mason and Pierce counties.
Of those, Phillips says close to 45,000 of the rainbow trout are larger-sized fish averaging 1-plus pounds apiece, and another 79,000 are steelhead averaging 11-inches.

The largest plant of steelhead will occur in Green Lake in the heart of Seattle located just north of Woodland Park with 10,000 fish.

STEELHEAD PLANTS 
Grays Harbor County plants will occur from Oct. 26-30 – Vance Creek 1 “Bowers”, 7,500; and Vance Creek 2 “Inez”, 1,000.
King County plants will occur from Oct. 26-30 – Angle, 8,000; Deep, 3,500; Fenwick, 1,500; Fivemile, 3,000; Holm, 1,500; Shadow, 4,000; Bitter, 1,500; and Green, 10,000.
Snohomish County plants will occur from Oct. 26-30 – Gissburg Pond North, 1,000; Gissburg Pond South, 2,000; and Tye, 4,000.
Thurston County plants will occur from Oct. 26-30 -St. Clair, 16,000.
King County plants will occur from Nov. 2-13 – Green, 5,000.
Snohomish County plants will occur from Nov. 2-13 – Gissburg Pond North, 500; and Gissburg Pond South, 1,000.
Thurston County plants will occur from Nov. 2-13 – St. Clair, 6,000.

Whatcom County plants will occur from Oct. 26-30 –Fazon, 2,000.
JUMBO RAINBOW TROUT PLANTS 
King County plants will occur from Oct. 12-16 – Beaver, 2,500.
Skagit County plants will occur from Oct. 12-16 – Grandy, 150.
Jefferson County plants will occur from Sept. 28-Oct. 2 – Gibbs, 350; Leland, 2,000; and Teal, 150.
Mason County plants will occur from Sept. 28-Oct. 2 – Isabella, 1,200; Island, 2,100; Lost, 2,400; Nahwatzel, 2,500; and Spencer, 5,500.
Pierce County plants will occur during week of Nov. 17 – American, 5,000; and Ohop, 500.
Pierce County plants will occur in mid-October – Bonney, 100; Bradley, 200; Harts, 350; and Kapowsin, 625.
Thurston County plants will occur during week of Nov. 17 – Black, 4,500; and Long, 2,000
Thurston County plants will occur in mid-October – Long’s Pond, 200; Munn, 500; Offutt, 1,000; St. Clair, 500; Lawrence, 500.
BLACK FRIDAY TROUT PLANTS 
(All lakes will be closed to fishing Nov. 23-26 to stock fish)
Lewis County (planted trout will average 1 pound apiece) – Fort Borst Park Pond, 2,000; and South Lewis Park Pond, 2,000.
Cowlitz County (planted trout will average 1 pound apiece) – Kress, 2,000.
Clark County (planted trout will average 1 pound apiece) – Battleground, 2,000; and Klineline, 2,000.
Klickitat County (planted trout will average 1 pound apiece) – Rowland, 2,000.
To follow the weekly trout plants, go to http://wdfw.wa.gov/fishing/plants/weekly/ .
 
Mark Yuasa : 206-464-8780 or myuasa@seattletimes.com ; on Twitter: @markkyuasa . Mark Yuasa covers fishing and outdoors in the Pacific Northwest.
